  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins\n- Informal anti-money laundering (AML) efforts date back to the 1920s\n- Initially targeted organized crime proceeds during Prohibition era\n- US Bank Secrecy Act of 1970 was first comprehensive regulatory framework\n\n2. International Development\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as global problem\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- 1990: First major international anti-money laundering conventions\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- US Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- US Bank Secrecy Act amendments\n- USA PATRIOT Act of 2001 significantly expanded reporting requirements\n- European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n\n4. Modern Regulatory Approach\n- Comprehensive reporting requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- International information sharing mechanisms\n\n5. Technological Adaptations\n- Increasing focus on cryptocurrency and digital transaction monitoring\n- Enhanced digital forensic capabilities\n- Ongoing regulatory updates addressing emerging financial technologies\n\nThe framework continues evolving to address increasingly complex financial criminal strategies.",
